From:Grantcw
Hello Paul,

I've seen in various posts from you throughout the years that you tend to like
Insurance company valuations if they have a price/book < 1.

How do you take into account earnings of a company? Say, for example, you have
two insurance companies. Both have a book value of $1 billion, but one had a
book value of $2 billion 5 years ago, and the other had a book value of $0.5
billion 5 years ago. So, one has been earning money and growing book value,
while the other has been losing money.

Looking primarily at book value, if they were both priced at a $1 billion
market cap, would they both be reasonably valued?

Or, say that you had two companies at a $1 Billion market cap with $1 Billion
book value, one had a p/e of 8 and the other had a p/e of 20?

I guess my overall question is, shouldn't earnings be a large part of the
valuation of any company, including an insurance company?

Thank you,

cw
