Date:4/21/2010 11:05:38 AM
From:Paul Senior
cwillyg. Yes, earnings. Per Dr. Graham, we don't want to see losses.

For insurance companies I tend to look at the balance sheet numbers before I
look at the earnings statement. I'd look at market cap as well as p/e and bv
for the insurance companies.

I'm looking for growing bv, so declining is a big negative for me. OTOH, we
have '08 or '09 where so many insurance companies reported declining bv and/or
earnings losses or high p/e's. I view that as an anomaly -- when I've had
courage to see things in that light.

Consider a company like Allstate last year. Sharply declining book value, price
below stated bv, earnings cratered. Likely - in retrospect anyway, or if
somebody had courage to believe in its business model, size, market presence,
etc. - that company would recover.

"...shouldn't earnings be a large part of the valuation of any company..."
Some companies are a value because of their assets vs. stock price, regardless
if they're if they're profitable now or haven't been for past years. My belief
anyway. Example might be JOE for land values. Some cash-rich net-nets.
Insurance companies though, they should be making money on their book and
float. So earnings - relatively low p/e - should usually be a criterion for a
buy decision.
%EOM----------------------

